content: 9/11/2001.  There I was.  31 years old.  Just getting ready to report when second plane hit.  Peter Jennings on my phone, asking what I saw, what people were saying. No Ch7 mic flag because we were going back and forth from local to network.  Today, while covering the relocation of the 9/11 Tribute Museum it was very tough, as the memories came crashing in.  Then I was taken to the side, asked to tell my story.  Me?  No way.  I explained the Smithsonian had requested our clothes but I threw them out.  Ok.  I will be a guide.   I think I can do it now.   It is so vitally important to tell young people how many souls in uniform (and not) ran to help.  My photographer today, Fred Mason, was also there (he also covered the 1993 bombing) and also agreed to volunteer as a guide.  We all must tell the story.
name: Michelle Charlesworth
title: Photos from Michelle Charlesworth's post

content: Forget $$$ overnight creams for anti-aging.  I wear La Roche Posay 60 every day of the year.  Don't forget your neck, chest and hands!  Sunscreen is the ticket.  Spray sunscreen?  Fine!  But ya gotta glisten.  Use a lot.  And reapply.  I tell my 10 and 7 year old to hold their breath outside when I spray them and to run away out of the cloud to breathe.  I hold mine and run the other way.  And I do their foreheads, faces, ears and necks with lotion and those sunscreen sticks that look like chapstick.  Favorite is Australian Gold.  Smells heavenly!  Tis the season!  Any tips for me?  I swear I spend about $250/year on sunscreen.  But no one in my family knows what a sunburn is!
name: Michelle Charlesworth
title: Are you applying spray-on sunscreen wrong? If so, you can still burn

content: "The Gong Show" is coming back!   I was 6 when it came on and I loved it.  Adults acting like idiots on TV.  I was hooked.  (And obviously inspired too!  😜😘). Chuck Barris (who just passed at 87 in March, sniffle) was so funny, clapping as he spoke, saying "we'll be back with more.... um, uh, STUFF", and introducing friends like "Gene, Gene the Dancing Machine".  I was on my feet on our tri-color shag carpet with them, shuffling and stretching out my arms.  Barris' brainchild, the Gong Show, was ready to go on the air when, in a last minute change, "Chuckie Baby" decided he would be the zany host, replacing the more straight guy who did not get the concept.  Brilliant.  Barris was a page at NBC (like my husband, Joe Torres, his wife Fran and many others) and Gong Show aired there, but ABC is bringing it baaaaaaack!
name: Michelle Charlesworth
title: The Gong Show w/Chuck Barris 1977

content: This came on TV when I was 6   and boy was I hooked!  I could not believe my eyes and ears.  Adults acting like idiots?!  Loved it.  Inspired by it.  😜😘.  Chuck Barris left us in March at age 87, gifting us memories of The Gong Show and so many other groundbreaking shows.  Barris (who was apparently shy) was not supposed to be the host, but when the original host did not get the wacky vibe of the show, stepped in to show us all how it's done.  "Gene, Gene the dancing machine" and Chuckie Baby had me on my feet on our tri-color shag carpet, shuffling and stretching out my arms.  He was as gentle and he was nutty.  Started as a page at NBC (like my husband, a lot of his friends, Joe Torres, his wife Fran and a tons of folks whose names you recognize), Chuck Barris brought The Gong Show to NBC but now ABC is starting a new version!  Excited to see it?

content: Just explained compound interest to someone 30 years of age who has $20,000 socked away in stocks for retirement.  I encouraged her to sock about the same away (in no load no fee index funds) every year, if possible, and to get on it, fast.  This is priority (before taxes and do not touch that 401k, period).  In 30 years, as what she makes off of her investment each year makes at least 5%, and it goes right back in to the pot to make more $$$$, she will probably have at least $1.6M.  And she will be a young 60 and hopefully have social security plus other investments.  Again, this is assuming 5% growth (conservative) from the stock market.  It could be more.  The numbers can be higher to start or lower, but teach (yourselves and) your kids about compounded interest.  Play around with a compound interest calculator.  It blows me away how many have no idea.  (I studied Econ in college and they did not drive this home!). Good book too: "Rich Dad, Poor Dad", which is why rich people and their kids stay rich!  Hint: they talk about this stuff, pay themselves first, just like this, and buy a lot of stuff at discount stores.  To the young: start early, while time is on your side.
name: Michelle Charlesworth
title: Compound Interest Calculator | Investor.gov

content:
American Medical Association: "first, do no harm."
This is part of the AMA's reaction to the Senate Health Care reform bill:

"Dear Majority Leader McConnell and Leader Schumer:
 
On behalf of the physician and medical student members of the American Medical Association (AMA), I am writing to express our opposition to the discussion draft of the “Better Care Reconciliation Act” released on June 22, 2017. Medicine has long operated under the precept of Primum non nocere, or “first, do no harm.”  The draft legislation violates that standard on many levels. "
name: Michelle Charlesworth

content:
Want to save money? Get serious about it?  Always pay yourself first -- get that saving habit locked in -- and live far beneath your means (unless of course you are scraping by).  Here are some interesting tips I was into reading.  Gotta work hard (2 jobs?!) and cut back.  Want more inspiration?  Read "The Millionaire Next Door."  
I just had a conversation with a smart woman about this same issue.  She chatted me up, then said she could not cut back to save, that she was pretty lean.   Then she laughed out loud as she walked to her $65,000 new car and I unlocked my 15 year old SUV.   Point made.  Nothing to say.  Pretty funny.
name: Michelle Charlesworth
title: 3 self-made millionaires share their No. 1 money-saving trick
